<font color="#FF0000">DEATH AND HELL ROLLED OVER</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug 30  6:09:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The smell of death!<br>
Oh! I know your name; I played your game. <br>
I called you often, fed you with my hands, touched you, caressed you.<br>
I purchased that black mantle that gave you fame. <br>
When I needed you the most, you turned coward and ran. <br>
You feared to walk with me in the night. <br>
I reached for you, I sang for you, I danced with you, gave you a kiss.<br>
But, you ran away the day anger and hatred controlled me. <br>
The day demons danced on little green tracers and laughed at me when they went by. <br>
You feared and trembled the day the dogs of war came out to play. <br>
That was the day God turned into night. <br>
The day gun barrels melted and all the horrors of horror came to the floor. <br>
Plants and animals, souls and spirits nothing was scared, nothing was spared. <br>
I saw you tremble and hide when the shadow of darkness would not come out to play, when the moon covered herself with dark clouds to hide the shame. <br>
I heard you weep like the widowed women without a song. <br>
You left us there in pain and agony because you could not endure what you saw, what my hands felt, when the smell of hot blood of good men mingled with my soul. <br>
It was then, I took your nametags and fed them to the dogs and angels sang their song. <br>
But you didn't want to finish the game. <br>

<p><code>-- Cook Barela, 1997   (Cook Barela) </code><p>


